TRMOR is a Turkish computational morphology which was developed by
Ayla Kayabas. It covers a large part of the Turkish morphology
including inflection, derivation and compounding.

The lexicon of TRMOR contains 36632 entries that each entry consists of many
different types of entries. See the paper for more information on the
features used in the lexicon.

Compilation
===========

Simply call the command
> make

Analysis
========

For interactive usage, use the command fst-mor

> fst-mor morph.a
reading automaton...
finished.
analyse> çiçeğim
çiçek<N><sg><POSS><1><sg><Nom>
çiçek<N><sg><POSS><1><sg><PRO><3><sg>
çiçek<N><sg><POSS><3><sg><PRO><1><sg>
çiçek<N><sg><PRO><1><sg>
çiçek<N><POSS><1><sg><Nom>
analyse> kalem
kalem<N><sg><Nom>
kalem<N><sg><PRO><3><sg>
kalem<N><Nom>
kale<N><sg><POSS><1><sg><Nom>
kale<N><sg><PRO><1><sg>
kale<N><POSS><1><sg><Nom>
analyse> çiçekseverim
çiçeksever<N><sg><POSS><1><sg><Nom>
çiçeksever<N><sg><POSS><1><sg><PRO><3><sg>
çiçeksever<N><sg><POSS><3><sg><PRO><1><sg>
çiçeksever<N><sg><PRO><1><sg>
çiçeksever<N><POSS><1><sg><Nom>
analyse> 
generate> çiçek<N><sg><PRO><1><sg>
çiçeğim
generate> q

Remark: Empty lines switch fst-mor between analysis and generation
mode. "q" terminates the program.


Otherwise use the faster command
> fst-infl2 morph.ca file
where "file" contains a list of words with one word per line.

TRMOR can be freely used for research, education and evaluation.

If you want to refer to TRMOR in a publication, please cite the
following article:

Ayla Kayabaş, Helmut Schmid, Ahmet E. Topcu, Özkan Kiliç
TRMOR: a finite-state-based morphological analyzer for Turkish
In: Turkish Journal of Electrical Engineering & Computer Sciences (TÜBITAK)
(2019) 27:3837-3851
URL: http://journals.tubitak.gov.tr/elektrik/issues/elk-19-27-5/elk-27-5-41-1902-125.pdf
